column3: * Image Super-resolution (SR) The term super-resolution (SR) can have different interpretations in different research communities: it can mean upsampling <cit.>, i.e. starting from the raw image  captured on a limited number of pixels and arriving at an estimate f̂, with a larger number of pixels within the same spatial support; it can also be interpreted as deblurring, where the blur kernel is a low-pass filter with transfer function equal to zero for spatial frequencies above cutoff <cit.>.
An extensive review on non-machine learning based methods of single-image SR (under the upsampling interpretation), is given in <cit.>.
To our knowledge, <cit.> is the first effort to use DNN in this context.
<cit.> are among the important follow-ups, where visually more appealing reconstructions are made possible with the use of perceptual loss<cit.> and Generative Adversarial Networks(GAN)<cit.>.

To our knowledge, the only prior work using DNNs on deblurring with a hard-cutoff in frequency imposed by the kernel was <cit.>, where the low-resolution image and high-resolution image within a training pair were captured using two lenses with different numerical apertures (NAs).

Traditional approaches for QPR include the Gerchberg-Saxton (GS) algorithm <cit.>, digital holography (DH) <cit.>, phase shifting interferometry <cit.>, and Transport of Intensity Equation (TIE) <cit.>.
Deep learning was introduced for QPR by Sinha et al <cit.> using an end-to-end residual convolutional neural network<cit.>.

Subsequently, Rivenson et al <cit.> proposed a QPR in a DH implementation with a DNN including an approximant: first  an approximate phase reconstruction was obtained using an optical back-propagation method; that reconstruction was then fed into the neural network for further improvement.
Goy et al <cit.> further showed that the GS algorithm is a good approximant for the DNN to perform QPR under conditions of low photon flux.

* Perceptual Quality Enhancement  Prior to <cit.>, it was realized that low-level pixel-wise losses generally encourage finding pixel-wise averages of plausible solutions which tend to be over-smooth<cit.>.

This strategy was applied to feature inversion by Mahendran et al<cit.>, to feature visualization by Simonyan et al<cit.> and Yosinski et al<cit.>, and to texture synthesis and style transfer by Gatys et al<cit.>.

Johnson et al<cit.> is the first work that combines the benefits of the fast rendering of output by a CNN and perceptual loss to train feed-forward convolutional neural networks for style transfer and SR.

Subsequently, Ledig et al<cit.> proposed a SR generative adversarial neural network<cit.>(SRGAN), where the perceptual loss based on high-level feature maps of the VGG-networks<cit.> and a discriminator, jointly encourage reconstructions to be perceptually indistinguishable from the high resolution images.
* Dual frequency band reconstruction In 2008, HiLo microscopy <cit.> was proposed by Lim et al to enhance the resolution of optical imaging system.
In 2018, Pan et al proposed a dual convolutional neural network (DualCNN)<cit.> structure consisting of two branches to solve low-level vision problems.

* Image Super-resolution (SR) The term super-resolution (SR) can have different interpretations in different research communities: it can mean upsampling <cit.>, i.e. starting from the raw image  captured on a limited number of pixels and arriving at an estimate f̂, with a larger number of pixels within the same spatial support; it can also be interpreted as deblurring, where the blur kernel is a low-pass filter with transfer function equal to zero for spatial frequencies above cutoff <cit.>.
